4. Principles of design and pricing of insurance products: 
(1) As part of product design and development cycle, every insurer shall ensure that:  
a. evolving risk coverage needs of the customer are taken into account while developing new products 
and revising existing products;  
b.  product covers an insurable risk with an underlying risk transfer; 
c. the products offered are simple to understand and not complex; 
d. there is transparency and clarity in wordings, terms, coverage, exclusions and conditions;  
e. policyholder’s interests are protected; 
f. the basic principles of insurance like insurable interest, indemnity, utmost good faith, proximate 
cause, contribution clause, salvage and subrogation etc. are adhered to; 
g. all the risks relevant to the products are appropriately considered in the pricing;  
h. the premium rates are fair and not excessive, inadequate, unfairly discriminatory and provide value 
for money; 
i. all relevant factors such as r isk appetite, capital availability, claim experience, reinsurance costs, 
guarantees, options are considered; 
j. products are viable and self-sustainable; 
k. market conduct practices are appropriat

